[{"id":29842,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dd28d7e4-cacd-4287-bde6-ff722a03f1f8-0d8420a0-34e7-40f1-9be6-a9896e227183-9757615_D.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8dfb8a13-cb39-44a7-9332-a8c59101b9c8-58c68ea3-1ee9-4630-802e-4e14f86421c0-9757615_C.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 105px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efee0a33-570a-461f-bb52-d8138c4ed8e4-83dc113a-4b06-4895-bfff-58007c5e0109-9757615_B.png\" style=\"width: 220px; height: 145px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bb91f14d-7d8a-465c-ac0f-5ad567a37dd1-57b5ea86-6b9d-4289-b2d5-f4d7a748e1f5-9757615_A.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 145px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The smaller the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pKa</mi></math>, the stronger the acid. The acidic nature of the compound depends on the stability of conjugate base.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efee0a33-570a-461f-bb52-d8138c4ed8e4-83dc113a-4b06-4895-bfff-58007c5e0109-9757615_B.png\" style=\"width: 219px; height: 144px;\" /></p><p>The stability of conjugate base formed by above compound is more stable than other three compounds given.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/de782b93-abee-47d9-ab34-1e681aed22f7-7edec1ce-6578-40fb-9c50-e7471d0791e7-image.png\" style=\"width: 328px; height: 114px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c0a1856-40a8-433b-900a-d839c91a0c88-d5177e1e-c195-40b7-9c38-4b7057f2f900-image.png\" style=\"width: 360px; height: 125px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c307468-d3d8-487a-ae68-7b581b7cf02b-8f27ac99-eee4-4d48-b350-a411d5cfd209-image.png\" style=\"width: 464px; height: 149px;\" /></p><p>So it has least <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pKa</mi></math> value.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29930,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Distance</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>travelled</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>by</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>compound</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Distance</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>travelled</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>by</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solvent</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>On chromatogram distance travelled by compound is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Distance travelled by solvent<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29753,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Nitrogen and Sulphur only","Nitrogen, Sulphur and Phosphorous Only","Phosphorous and halogens only","Nitrogen, Sulphur, and halogens"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Lassaigne's test helps to detect Nitrogen, Sulphur, and Halogens in organic compounds. Here, sodium metal <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>Na</mi></mfenced></math> is heated in the presence of the organic compound inside a fusion tube. The primary objective of this test is that all the available elements are converted by Sodium metal <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>Na</mi></mfenced></math> into the ionic state. Lassaigne test reaction for sodium is given below:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>NaCN</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Na</mi><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>Na</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>NaX</mi></math></p><p>In the third experiment, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math> can be anything such as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>Br</mi></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29808,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In the first step of the reaction, protonation of alcohol takes place and carbocation is formed after removal of water. The carbocation formed undergo rearrangement to get stability. In the given, methyl shift takes place to convert secondary carbocation to tertiary carbocation. The alpha hydrogen to the positive&nbsp;charged carbon are involved in hyperconjugation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9113451c-d035-419d-be50-7e921d6fee43-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 452px;\" /></p><p>So, number of hyperconjugation structures in most stable carbocation</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>7</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30031,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3>\\mathrm{HCHO}$","$\\mathrm{HCHO}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}>\\mathrm{HCHO}>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3>\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}>\\mathrm{HCHO}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Presence of alkyl group in carbonyl compounds decreases their reactivity towards nucleophilic addition. Further greater the number of such groups lesser will be the reactivity towards nucleophilic addition $\\therefore$ correct order is\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e3-car6NAUWm878ywL2eU_Y-eP_Wo5mdVl4xiEtxKzw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":29693,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both <strong> Statement (I)</strong> and<strong> Statement (II)</strong> are false.","Both <strong> Statement (I)</strong> and<strong> Statement (II)</strong> are true.","<strong> Statement (I)</strong> is false but<strong> Statement (II)</strong> is true.","<strong> Statement (I)</strong> is true but<strong> Statement (II)</strong> is false."],"answer":1,"solution":"Statement-I $\\rightarrow$ True\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cXxE3dTZFz0xuFeP6Wbt8oIrirm863d8DfPh_QLqEK0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\nBoth are ring chain isomers \nStatement-II $\\rightarrow$ True<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Un_8AlhBdUsfh7qK40IHL4aNXE_XzdO6WH6f2Bck9dc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\n$1^{\\circ}$ Amine and $2^{\\circ}$ Amine are different functional groups, hence both are functional group isomers.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29758,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p>Reducing agent</p>","Catalytic agent","Hydrolysis agent","Oxidising agent"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Kjeldahl's method is used for the estimation of nitrogen. The organic compound is heated with conc. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> in presence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> and a little <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CuSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> to convert all the nitrogen into <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>.</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> raises the boiling point of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> while <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CuSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> catalyses the reaction.</p><p>Hence, B is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29852,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Partition chromatography is based on continuous differential partitioning of components of a mixture between stationary and mobile phases. Paper chromatography is a type of partition chromatography. In paper chromatography, a special quality paper known as chromatography paper is used. Chromatography paper contains water trapped in it, which acts as the stationary phase.</p><p>The relative partition&nbsp;of each component of the mixture is expressed in terms of its retardation factor i.e. R<sub>f</sub> value</p><p>R<sub>f</sub> =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>distance</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>travel</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>by</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solute</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>from</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>base</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>line</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>distance</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>travel</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>by</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solvent</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>from</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>base</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>line</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30044,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5WZhZ95ptbMTYtwYFasPPo4ZK0TX17_TQHgafIbcXrk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wxywQ6X1dKo-uOPJjR0cqu7MJaJLFRrpGNwkRkwXauM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8ztBxjvhkI-99iPc5HXsBAUg5E3KOph8tJK_wBN5m1E.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VFVi3OKjc0cvYR_QtL5bnp-temWYtQR1SFT2mM7zBXM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"The plane of polarized light is rotated by optically active compound, i.e. it should be chiral. \nSo, (A) has, chiral $\\mathrm{C-}$atom. So, it is optically active.\nIn (B), (C) and (D) plane of symmetry is present.\nHence, (A) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":30007,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Lactic acid","Tartaric acid","Maleic acid","$\\alpha$-amino acids"],"answer":2,"solution":"Optical isomers contain an asymmetric (chiral) carbon atom (a carbon atom attached to four different atoms or groups). Therefore all except maleic acid exhibit optical isomerism.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29718,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cLbw1IhGKhvopAYN83kWpBhKGUCE2EyoSrknXEeSR0E.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30066,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["From a mixed precipitate of $\\mathrm{AgCl}$ and $\\mathrm{AgI}$, ammonia solution dissolves only $\\mathrm{AgCl}$","Ferric ions give a deep green precipitate on adding potassium ferrocyanide solution","On boiling a solution having $\\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ and $\\mathrm{HCO}_3^{-}$ions we get a precipitate of $\\mathrm{K}_2 \\mathrm{Ca}\\left(\\mathrm{CO}_3\\right)_2$.","Manganese salts give a violet borax bead test in the reducing flame"],"answer":0,"solution":"Ammonia can dissolve ppt. of Agcl only due to formation of complex as given below:\n$\\mathrm{AgCl}+2 \\mathrm{NH}_3 \\rightarrow\\left[\\mathrm{Ag}\\left(\\mathrm{NH}_3\\right)_2\\right] \\mathrm{Cl}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":29770,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a8b504f6-fe13-4998-9dff-2d0a429b96c9.png\" style=\"width: 246px; height: 146px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5d146e0d-2212-45ca-a91b-f1ced731df3b.png\" style=\"width: 234px; height: 147px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/178120d2-398e-415a-893e-fd67d8009ecc.png\" style=\"width: 178px; height: 140px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/06126888-05cb-482f-ad4a-59e613584d8a.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 186px;\"/>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The key difference between allylic and vinylic carbon is that allylic carbon is the carbon atom adjacent to the double-bonded carbon atom, whereas the vinylic carbon atom is one of the two atoms that share the double bond.</p><p>Haloarene or aryl halide is a chemical compound containing arenas, where one or more hydrogen atoms are bonded to the aromatic ring and are replaced with halogens.</p><p>Vinyl carbon is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> hybridized aliphatic carbon</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0a966c65-905f-461c-8bbe-579dd6e03ae6.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 412px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29655,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given data:<br>Mass of organic compound ($w$) = $0.50$ g<br>Volume of nitrogen gas ($V_1$) = $70$ mL<br>Temperature ($T_1$) = $300$ K<br>Total pressure = $715$ mm Hg<br>Aqueous tension = $15$ mm Hg<br>Pressure of dry nitrogen ($P_1$) = $715 - 15 = 700$ mm Hg<br>Convert the volume of nitrogen to STP conditions ($P_0 = 760$ mm Hg, $T_0 = 273$ K):<br>Using the combined gas law: $\\frac{P_1 V_1}{T_1} = \\frac{P_0 V_0}{T_0}$<br>$V_0 = \\frac{P_1 V_1 T_0}{P_0 T_1} = \\frac{700 \\times 70 \\times 273}{760 \\times 300} \\approx 58.68$ mL<br>At STP, $22400$ mL of $N_2$ weighs $28$ g.<br>Mass of $N_2$ collected = $\\frac{28 \\times 58.68}{22400}$ g<br>Percentage of nitrogen = $\\frac{\\text{Mass of } N_2}{\\text{Mass of compound}} \\times 100$<br>$\\% N = \\frac{28 \\times 58.68}{22400 \\times 0.50} \\times 100$<br>$\\% N = \\frac{28 \\times 58.68}{112} = \\frac{58.68}{4} = 14.67 \\%$<br>Rounding to the nearest integer, we get $15$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29993,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl cyclohexane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Dimethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ethyl cyclohexane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Dimethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ethyl cyclohexane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl cyclohexane"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ebkofzlfjtrahvgzrvuyeufdmfnheikrbeezldzspwfpozmmqz.jpeg\" /></p><p>Six membered cyclic ring will be the root chain. It is an alkane with only single bonds so suffix &quot;ane&quot; will be used. The IUPAC name of the compound will be.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl cyclohexane</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29811,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Cytosine","A nucleotide","Methionine&nbsp;","Chloroxylenol"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Barium chloride is used estimate sulphur content in the molecule. In Carius tube&nbsp;test, a known mass of sulphur present in an organic compound with Silver Nitrate is heated into a sealed tube known as Carius tube with silver. The organic compound is then converted to Sulphuric acid which then reacts with excess Barium Chloride solution and produces a precipitate of Barium Sulphate.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math></p><p>It is clear that &quot; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math> &quot; must contain sulphur. Methionine is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>11</mn></msub><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>, a sulphur contaning amino acid</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29959,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methylprop<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ynyl)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>heptene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>propylhept<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo></math>en<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>yne","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>propyl hept<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>en<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo></math>yne","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methylprop<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>enhyl)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>heptyne"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7c9c34ea-9ecd-46aa-a8fe-3e434b5eeb74-image24.png\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>propyl hept<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>en<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><m