mathrm{S}=\\frac{466}{233} \\\\ & \\text { Mass of } \\mathrm{S}=\\frac{466}{233} \\times 32 \\mathrm{mg} \\\\ & =64 \\mathrm{mg} \\\\ & \\% \\mathrm{~S}=\\frac{64}{160} \\times 100=40 \\%\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29995,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>  and AgCN are soluble in acidic medium.","Silver halides are totally insoluble in nitric acid.","<math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> and <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> , if present, are decomposed by conc. <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> and hence do not interfere in the test.","Ag reacts faster with halides in acidic medium"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> and <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> ions if present are decomposed by conc. <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> and hence do not interfere in the test.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29980,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;Values are a measure of basicity. Higher the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;value, greater will be basicity.<br /><br />(I) Basic character &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi><mtext>&#8201;s-&#8201;character</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> has more % s-character than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> so it is less basic as compare to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> Hence <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>.</mo></math><br /><br />(II) In the (ii) structure lone pair present on the N atom is involved in aromaticity so, it is difficult to donate. Hence, least basic<br /><br />Thus, the correct order will be: <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29888,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>N&nbsp;in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>-dimethylaminopentane <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>57</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>115</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>mol</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>17</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>45</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>CuO</mi><mo>&#10230;</mo><mn>7</mn><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>17</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>45</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>Cu</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mtext>&#160;no. molesof CuO reacted&#160;</mtext><mrow><mn>45</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>&#160;no. molesof&#160;</mtext><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>17</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mtext>&#160;reacted&#160;</mtext></mrow><mn>1</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> no. of moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CuO</mi></math> reacted <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>45</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1125</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30004,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>24</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>48</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math> <mrow> <mtext>R</mtext> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>Br</mtext> <mover> <mo>&#8594;</mo> <mtext>Carius method</mtext> </mover> <mtext>AgBr</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>250</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mg</mi></math> organic compound is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RBr</mi></math>.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>141</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mg</mi><mo>AgBr</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>141</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>80</mn><mn>188</mn></mfrac><mi>mg</mi><mo>Br</mo></math><br />From principle of atom coservation(POAC), mass of Bromine is conserved in reactant and product</p><p>So, mass of Bromine in organic compound =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>141</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>80</mn><mn>188</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math>&nbsp;of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Br</mi></math> in organic compound =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Br</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>compound</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mn>5</mn><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mn>0</mn><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>24%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29754,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math></p><p>Equivalent of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo></math>Equivalent of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math></p><p>moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></msub></mfenced></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mn>1000</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>                                            <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo></mrow></msup><mi>moles</mi></math></p><p>Moles of nitrogen<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi>moles</mi></math></p><p>Weight of Nitrogen<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>14</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>56</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p>Percent of nitrogen<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>56</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>weight</mi><mo> </mo><mi>of</mi><mo> </mo><mi>the</mi><mo> </mo><mi>compound</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>100</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>56</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>56</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29997,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ajnasjhbd.jpg\" style=\"width: 212px; height: 164px;\" /><br /><br /><br /><strong>at 2 Carbon</strong><br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/jbslgyregkreg.JPG\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 226px;\" />&nbsp;<br /><br />&nbsp;Rotation is clockwise, but lowest priority group is on horizontal line so configuration will be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math><br /><br /><strong>at 3 Carbon</strong><br />&nbsp;<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/vsdnvgjkasjsgfsh.JPG\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 245px;\" /><br />Rotation is anticlockwise and lowest priority group is on horizontal line so, configuration will be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math><br /><br />&there4; Configuration is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math>.<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30047,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["2-bromo-6-chlorocyclohex-1-ene","6-bromo-2-chlorocyclohexene","3-bromo-1-chlorocyclohexene","1-bromo-3-chlorocyclohexene"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":29746,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(A) - (IV), (B) - (III), (C) - (I), (D) - (II)","(A) - (I), (B) - (II), (C) - (IV), (D) - (III)","(A) - (III), (B) - (I), (C) - (II), (D) - (IV)","(A) - (II), (B) - (IV), (C) - (III), (D) - (I)"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8xmbyBh6X83nVm0WfM7QkPQdfkA-28AI8jchOxEV9sM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29634,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":2,"solution":"Statement I: Metamerism arises due to different alkyl chains on either side of a polyvalent functional group. In ketones, the carbonyl group ($>C=O$) acts as the polyvalent functional group. In $2,6$-diethylcyclohexanone, the alkyl groups attached to the $\\alpha$-carbons are two ethyl groups. In $6$-methyl-$2$-n-propylcyclohexanone, the alkyl groups are a methyl group and an n-propyl group. Since the alkyl groups around the carbonyl group are different while the molecular formula remains the same, they are metamers. Thus, Statement I is true.<br><br>Statement II: For a ketone to exhibit keto-enol tautomerism, it must have at least one $\\alpha$-hydrogen atom. In $2,2,6,6$-tetramethylcyclohexanone, the $\\alpha$-carbons (C$2$ and C$6$) are bonded to two methyl groups each. Since there are no $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms present, it cannot undergo keto-enol tautomerism. Thus, Statement II is false.<br><br>Answer: Statement I is true but Statement II is false","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30008,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/25978_1.JPG\" style=\"width: 209px; height: 120px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/25978_2.JPG\" style=\"width: 204px; height: 130px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/25978_3.JPG\" style=\"width: 192px; height: 135px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/25978_4.JPG\" style=\"width: 207px; height: 83px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>Ph</mtext></mrow> <mtext>3</mtext> </msub> <msup> <mtext>C</mtext> <mo>&#8226;</mo> </msup> <mtext>&#8196;</mtext><mtext>&#8203;</mtext><mtext>&#62;</mtext><mtext>&#8196;</mtext><mfenced> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>CH</mtext></mrow> <mtext>3</mtext> </msub> </mrow> </mfenced><msup> <mtext>C</mtext> <mo>&#8226;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math><br />In <math> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>Ph</mtext></mrow> <mtext>3</mtext> </msub> <msup> <mtext>C</mtext> <mo>&#8226;</mo> </msup> <msup> <mtext>e</mtext> <mo>&#8722;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> undergoes in delocalization while <math> <mrow> <mfenced> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mtext>CH</mtext></mrow> <mtext>3</mtext> </msub> </mrow> </mfenced><msup> <mtext>C</mtext> <mo>&#8226;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> is stable due to the <math> <mrow> <mtext>+I</mtext></mrow> </math> and hyperconjugation effect of <math> <mrow> <mo>&#8722;</mo><msub> <mrow> <mtext>CH</mtext></mrow> <mtext>3</mtext> </msub> </mrow> </math> group, because resonance is a predominant factor so the order is above one.<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29946,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CHBr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2804b3ae-186b-4e38-a332-37df7311334d-image.png\" style=\"width: 89px; height: 172px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fee8a85c-00b9-4e82-9f5c-f664dc387672-image.png\" style=\"width: 135px; height: 166px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29894,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math> Trichloro ethane <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7031e97c-17d2-4476-981b-9951f956bfcb-conform.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 247px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29915,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(B) and (C) only","(A) only","(A) and (C) only","(B) only"],"answer":2,"solution":"Ambident nucleophile<br />(A) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCN</mi><mo>&#38;</mo><mi>AgCN</mi></math><br />(C) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#38;</mo><msub><mi>KNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29925,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;and Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;are true","Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;is true but Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;is false","Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;is false but Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;is true","Both Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;and Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;are false"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;of chloroform <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>334</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;of aniline&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>457</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p>thus can be seprated of simple distillation.</p><p>Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;: Mixture of aniline and water seprated by simple distillation.</p><p>A suitable method for separating a mixture of aniline and chloro form would be steam distillation. Steam distillation is the process used to separate aromatic compound from a mixture because of their temperature sensitivity. Therefore, steam distillation is an ideal method for their separation</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29764,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A-IV, B-I, C-II, D-III","A-IV, B-III, C-II. D-I","A-I. B-II, C-IV, D-III","A-II, B-III. C-I, D-IV"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A mixture of chloroform and aniline can be separated by distillation. The boiling point of chloroform is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>°</mo></math>C, and that of aniline is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>189</mn><mo>°</mo></math>C. Therefore, distillation can be used to separate a mixture of chloroform and aniline.</p><p><b>Fractional distillation</b> is the process by which oil refineries separate crude oil into different, more useful hydrocarbon products based on their relative molecular weights in a distillation tower.</p><p>Steam Distillation is a separation process for temperature-sensitive substances. It is a particular type of distillation. Another way around is a method for separating miscible liquid bases depending upon their volatilities. Aniline - Water mixture can be separated by this technique.</p><p>For separating glycerol from spent-lye is distillation under reduced pressure because glycerol has a high boiling point and since in this method the external pressure is lowered, it boils at a lower temperature.</p><p>Hence option B is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]